  <!-- Page 8: Crossing Over -->
  <div class="page" id="page8">
    <h1>‚ûî Crossing Over</h1>
    <p><strong>Crossing over</strong> is the process during <strong>meiosis</strong> where homologous chromosomes exchange genetic material. While the chromosomes are paired in <strong>tetrads</strong>, sections of chromatids from one chromosome are <strong>swapped</strong> with sections from the corresponding chromatid of its <strong>homologous</strong> partner. This exchange results in <strong>recombined chromatids</strong>, where new combinations of genes are formed. This increases genetic diversity in the offspring. <strong>Crossing over</strong> occurs at specific points called <strong>chiasmata</strong> and is a crucial step for ensuring variability in the resulting gametes.</p>


    <p style="font-weight: bold; color: #222; background-color:#ff3b86; padding: 10px; border-radius: 8px;">
      üöÄ Drag and drop the events happening during crossing over!
    </p>


    <div class="drag-container">
