  <!-- Page 14: Metaphase II -->
<div class="page" id="page14">
    <h1>‚ûî Metaphase II</h1>
    <p>In <strong>Metaphase II</strong> of meiosis, the <strong>chromosomes</strong> align along the <strong>metaphase plate</strong> in both haploid cells. Unlike in Metaphase I, where homologous chromosomes pair up, in Metaphase II, the chromosomes line up individually, with each chromosome consisting of two sister chromatids. The spindle fibers attach to the centromeres of each chromosome, preparing them for separation in the next phase. This alignment ensures that each daughter cell will receive one chromatid from each chromosome.</p>
    <p style="font-weight: bold; color: #222; background-color: #ff3b86; padding: 10px; border-radius: 8px;">
      üöÄ Drag and drop the events happening during Metaphase II!
    </p>
